# DevOps and CI/CD Overview

---
# 1. Introduction to DevOps

DevOps is a modern software development methodology that brings together the **Development (Dev)** and **Operations (Ops)** teams. It focuses on collaboration, automation, and continuous improvement to deliver software quickly and reliably.

## Objectives of DevOps

- Accelerate software delivery
- Enhance team collaboration
- Automate repetitive processes
- Improve software quality
- Reduce deployment failures

---

# 2. DevOps Lifecycle

The DevOps lifecycle consists of the following phases:

1. Plan
2. Develop
3. Build
4. Test
5. Release
6. Deploy
7. Operate
8. Monitor

### Lifecycle Flow

```text
Plan
   ↓
Develop
   ↓
Build
   ↓
Test
   ↓
Release
   ↓
Deploy
   ↓
Operate
   ↓
Monitor
```

---

# 3. What is CI/CD?

CI/CD stands for **Continuous Integration** and **Continuous Deployment (or Continuous Delivery)**.

## Continuous Integration (CI)

Continuous Integration is the practice of automatically building and testing code whenever developers push changes to the repository.

### Advantages

- Detects bugs early
- Improves code quality
- Faster development
- Easy collaboration

---

## Continuous Delivery (CD)

Continuous Delivery prepares the application for deployment after successful testing.

### Advantages

- Reliable software releases
- Faster deployment
- Reduced release risks

---

## Continuous Deployment

Continuous Deployment automatically deploys every successful change to production without manual intervention.

---

# 4. CI/CD Pipeline

```text
Developer
     │
     ▼
Write Code
     │
     ▼
Push to GitHub
     │
     ▼
Continuous Integration
(Build + Test)
     │
     ▼
Continuous Delivery
     │
     ▼
Continuous Deployment
     │
     ▼
Production Server
     │
     ▼
Monitoring
```

